#include <vector>
#include <unordered_map>

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findAllPeople(int n, vector<vector<int>>& meetings, int firstPerson) {
        unordered_map<int, int> personSeen;
        vector<int> result;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (auto meeting : meetings[i]) {
                if (personSeen.find(meeting[0]) != personSeen.end()) {
                    result.push_back(meeting[1]);
                }
            }
        }

        return result;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n * (n - 1) * (n - 2) * ... * 2 * 1
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

We use a hash map (unordered_map) to store the person's index as the key and the person's index as the value. We iterate through all meetings and check if the person at meeting[0] is already in the hash map. If found, we add the person at meeting[1] to the result vector. This approach has a high efficiency because we only need to iterate through meetings once and hash map lookups are constant time operations. The time complexity is O(n * (n - 1) * (n - 2) * ... * 2 * 1, which is O(n^2). The space complexity is O(n) due to the hash map. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only requires a constant amount of energy to perform the hash map lookups and vector operations.

